        <body>       
                 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Mercantile Library&#44; Jan. 10. 88.<lb/>
                Rev. S. Morais&#44; Philada.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. A. J. Gordon of<lb/> Boston has published a letter<lb/> signed Alfred A. Marcus&#44;<lb/> Boston&#44; whom D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. Gordon<lb/> speaks of as &#34;one of the most<lb/> prominent and intelligent<lb/> Hebrews in our city belong&#45;<lb/>ing to the extreme Orthox school.&#34;<lb/>  In this letter Mr. Marcus names<lb/> yourself along with Rev. H. P.<lb/> Mendes and others as sustain&#45;<lb/>ing his statement.  He says&#45;&#45;<lb/> &#34;no fermented liquors are<lb/> allowed in our Passover ser&#45;<lb/>vices&#44; or even in our dwellings&#44;<lb/> and in all my experience as<lb/> a Hebrew I have never known<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>fermented wine to be used in<lb/> that rite &#38;c.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>It seems to me that men<lb/> who make such declarations<lb/> do not know what we mean<lb/> by the word &#34;<hi rend="underline">fermented</hi>.&#34;  They<lb/> must&#44; I think&#44; take this word<lb/> to involve the idea of yeast a<lb/> grain ferment&#59; while <hi rend="underline">we</hi> have<lb/> reference to <hi rend="underline">the spontaneous<lb/> working of the grape&#45;juice<lb/> itself</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>I desire to ask you one<lb/> question&#58; Have you ever known<lb/> a recognized and well&#45;educated<lb/> minister of your faith who<lb/> has objected to the imported<lb/> Passover wine&#44; duly certified&#44;<lb/> on the ground that it was a<lb/> <hi rend="underline">leavened</hi> article&#44; because it<lb/> had passed through the spon&#45;<lb/>taneous working which con&#45;<lb/>verts the juice into wine&#63;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Are not Israelites at liberty to<lb/> use the <hi rend="underline">imported</hi> Passover wine in the<lb/> Passover observances if they can<lb/> procure it&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Do not the Israelites in Hungary<lb/> and other wine countries use&#44;<lb/> at Passover&#44; grape wine&#44; prop&#45;<lb/>erly prepared&#44; which has been<lb/> fermented&#63;<lb/></p>
                
            <p>It is wonderful how this sub&#45;<lb/>ject is treated in our country&#33;<lb/>  Why can we not cause all to<lb/> know precisely what <hi rend="underline">is</hi> the<lb/> tradition and the view of the<lb/> Jewish religion as to this mat&#45;<lb/>ter of Passover Wine&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Please to favor me&#44; as you<lb/> have kindly done already.<lb/>
                With much respect<lb/>
                Yours&#44;<lb/> S. C. Brace.<lb/></p>
            </body>
